27 May 2020 23:25






Here are my thoughts on it;

+Show

-Hide


I'm deeply invested in philosophy relating to the known vs the unknown, as well as other similar concepts. Through reading on postmodernism and culture, I found myself to be repulsed by the fascination that contemporary philosophers give to the nature of unbeing, unreality, etc. I think 5005 is an appropriate allegory for humanity's general nature of fighting against the darkness, despite the intrigue of the unknown seeming far more appealing. I think that Ramirez' drifting into madness, plus the general disgust at the cultures and  of Lamplight, can be seen as someone going too far from humanity in order to understand the world (similar to postmodernism and the fates of many of their prominent philosophers) and in this case- meeting the abyss, and finding it to be unwelcoming of the human's curiosity. But what do I know?

The night does not give such easy answers.

-Hide



